{"/service/ndnp/whi/batch_whi_lenawee_ver01/data/sn85040652/00514158976/1921012901/0040.xml":{"full_text":"NEIGHBORHOOD NEWS NOTES\nMERCER\n-I. Hein of Hurley was here with the\nwrecker and biircrew to repair dam\nages done by lid\u2019s engine on Tuesday\nmorning.\nMiss Gladys Gleason entertained\nthe Birthday Club at the home of Mrs.\nWm. Miller last Friday.\nWalter llofGnan was an Iron wood\ncaller Saturday\nMrs. Frank Allen spent Saturday\nwith her sister, Mrs. Otto Layman,\nat Manitowish.\nJohn Karnpe went to Rhinelander\nThursday to consult a physician.\nIVter and Klnier Erickson and Carl'\nHendrickson of Tigertown visited\nfriends here over Sunday.\nWalter I'eter, who has beeuemploy\ned by Max Feter, cutting logs, was\nquite seriously injured by a falling\ntree striking his head which caused\nconcussion of the brain. He was tak\nen to Dr. Anderson's hospital at Iron\nwood last Saturday, and an operation\nperformed. At last reports the young\nman was getting along nicely. Ilis\nborne is at Menominee, Wig.\nMrs. L. A. Gehr and Mrs. D. L.\nWhite were shoppers at Ironwood and\nHurley last Monday.\nMrs. W. J. Schi\u00dfeman and Mrs.\nWm. Miller were Ironwood visitors\nlast Thursday.\nEarl Brown of Wakefield, spent\nSunday here.\nMrs. M. E. Brandt returned from\na trip to Milwaukee last Tuesday\nmorning, Mr. Brandt will return later.\nMr. and Mrs. Jack Shea arid Mrs.\nH. E. Savacore were Hurley callers\nSaturday.\nAllen Pemble and wife moved back\non their farm near town Tuesday, he\nhaving finished his logging job at\nFine Lake, He will now be employed\nby C. Champine at the landing here.\nMrs. Y r V. Hadly returned from an\nextended trip to Detroit, Michigan,\nlast Wednesday.\nMrs. Lee Doriot of Manitowish en\ntertained the Ladies Aid Wednesday.\nThe following ladies from here atten\nded the meeting: Mrs. Chas. Moffett,\nMrs. J E. Hudson, Mrs. Wm. Hobbs,\nMrs. Sara Sargent and Mrs. W. J.j\nSchilleman.\nBorn to Mr. and Mrs. Levi Sleight\na son Jan. 26.\nT T. Ryan of Green Bav wasa busi\nness caller here Wednesday.\nMrs. John Ferry and daughter\nMargaret left Thursday for Merrill,\nMrs. Ferry having just received a\nmessage stating her daughter-in-law\nwas seriously ill.\nMr. and Mrs. Merton McMann, left\nTuesday for a few days visit at their\nhome at Ashland.\nMrs. Denuie Schultz and ehilflren I\nof Park Falls, arrived Wednesday for\na visit at the Mrs. 11. I\u2019emble home.\nThe Basket Ball team of the Mercer\nschool will have a game with the\nWinchester school team here Satur-i\nday evening. The boys are spending\nevery spare moment practising so\nthey will tie prepared for the worst.i\nHere's hoping you win boys, and show\nthe hometolks what you ean do.\nGURNEY.\n.Mrs. John Lundgren, and her\nsister-in-law, Mrs. Edward Johnston,\nof Barker, went to Ashland last Mon\nday.\nMr. and Mrs. Martin Paterson, re\nturned to their home here last Mon-!\nday, after an extended visit to their\nfolks at Ilennansville, Michigan.\nMrs. Frank Marith left for a visit\nto her people at Butternut. Jan. 24.\nMie expects to be gone about two\nWeeks,\nWhats the best Title\nto this\nGoodrich Wctoie?\nir~; r i\nv; /Goodrich\nf tf\\\u201cHi-Press\"\ni\njr>-\\ \u201e>^r\n\nForty different money prize** ranging\nFrom $250 to slo\u2014 costs you nothing\nto submit a title.\nContest runs from January Ist to April\nSend your suggestion to the B. F.\nGoodrich Rubber Company m either\nNew York. Boston, Chicago, Kansas\nCity, Seattle, Denver or Akron\u2014and\nwhen next you buy rubber boots or\nshoes insist on the kind with the Red\nLine 'Round the Top.\nGoodrich\nRubber Footwear\nMr. and Mrs. LaVHle m.eie a shoe\nvisit to their relatives at Hurley, last\ni week.\nFrau\u00a3 Hodak was here collecting\ntaxes last Monday. He will be here\nagain Jan. 29th.\nMiss Margaret Hardie, supervising\nteacher, spent a halfday at the Gur\nney School fast Monday, ''tie gave\nArithmetic tests to the pupils.\nMiss Ovidia Johnson entertained a\nnumber of her friends at a birthday\nparty last Tuesday evening. She re\nceived many beautiful and useful\ngifts. Games were played and a\ndelightful lunch was served.\nLast Saturday cud Sunday the\nyoung people-took out the big town\nbobsled and slid down tlie icy Limey\nhill. They also slid evenings as the\nnights weie moonlight. Saturday nite\nafter sliding, they went up to the\nSchool Hail and had a short informal\ndance, after which they told stories\nand adjourned home.\nThe Merry Makers\u2019Club of Gurney,\nheld their regular twice-a-month\nmeeting last Wednesday. Roal Peter\nson was unanimously elected presid\nent, to succeed 11. Rice, who\ntendered Ins resignation at the last\nmeeting. Miss Julia Wagner also\nresigned her position as treasurer of\nthe Club. Miss Emileua Martinka\nwas choseu to succeed tier.\nNelson La Valle, of Fargo, X. I).,\nIs here for an extended visit with\nhis parents, Mr. and Mrs. La Valle,\nand his sister, Mrs. J. Martinka.\nEmil Frauzen, of Saxon, spent the\nweek-end at Peter Peterson\u2019s.\nMiss Fearl Young, whe is employed\nat DeFer\u2019s store at Saxon, spent the\nweek-end with her folks here.\nF. W. Gray and daughter, Mrs. A.\nA. Morse, and her son Frank went to\nIronwood last Tuesday. They went to\nreceive medical advice concerning her\nsou Frank who has been in poor health\nas a result of an attack of infiamalory\nrheumatism.\nF. W. Gray went to Hurley and\nIronwood last Wednesday on business.\nMiss Virgie Duffy, who has been\nstaying with relatives at Upson, came\nhere Wednesday for a visitwithfi iends\nand relatives. She will remain for the\nbaseball dance Saturday and go hack\nto Upson Monday.\nSam Diugman, who was visiting at\nhis home for the past two weeks,\nwent to Superior Thursday to work.\nLeo. Koepack, who was employed\nat. Ironwood came here Wednesday\nfor a short visit at the J. Martinka\nhome.\nMiss Genevieve Cadd, a pupil of the\nGurney school, who has been visiting\nat her home at Boniface, Mich., sent\nword to her triends hereof the arrival\nof a new baby sister at her home.\nWhiskey Consumption Decreases.\nWhisky consumption in the United\nStates decreased from 89,04 1 ,98r, gal\nlons in 1917 to 5,551,r>\u00bb:1 gallons m 1920,\naccording to figures announced by the\nAnti-saloon league of America.\nConsumption of alcohol in the same\nyears decreased from 71,0*1,1-1 gal\nlons to 22,089,:tr>5 gallons, the figures\nshowed, while beer consumption\ndropped from t50,5i7,279 barrels to\n9,201,280 barrels.\n\u201cGranting that many million gal\nlons of alcohol and whisky w ithdrawn\nfor nonbeverage use have been di\nverted to beverage use,\u201d said a state\nment by the league \"and granting\nthat many million gallons of beer\nhave been made and consumed ille\ngally, a conservative estimate shows\nthat the people of tlie United States\nhave saved over $1,000,000 previous\nly spent for beverage intoxicants.\"\nIB 0 N COUNTY NEWS. HUXLEY, WIS.\nCOUNTY SCHOOL NEWS\nPrepared by Miss Ida Bradley, Co. Supt. of\nSchools, and Mias Margaret Hardie, Su\npervising Teacher.\n\u2014k\nThe Upson school instructor, Miss\nPauline Gutowski, had a pleasant moth\ners\u2019 meeting last Friday in the school.\nAfter an informal program given by the\npupils, a dainty lunch was served to the\nmothers.\nThe following is a letter received from\nthe Near East Relief Committee:\nTo the Teachers and Pupils of the Schools\nof Wisconsin.\nThe children of sorrow once more\nstand before you. They are rendered\nhomeless and hungry but they are not\nhopeless. In their simple faith they turn\ntrustingly to their more fortunate sisters\nand brothers of rich and prosperous\nAmerica.\nChildren of Sorrow! There are un\ncommon thousands of them; hundreds of\nthousands under American care. It is\nan appalling number of pitiful orphan\nwards the Near East Relief must shelter\nunder its wings. There is now a table\ntwenty-four miles long which the boys\nand girls and mothers and fathers of\nAmerica must furnish with food.\nFatherless and motherless these are\nthe children of Armenians, Syrians and I\nJews, made homeless and dependent by i\nthe atrocities of the Turks.\nA diet of bread for breakfast, bread\nand soup for dinner and bread for supper,\nyet this slender ration means life to them, j\nSeventeen cents a day or five dollars a\nmonth will feed and save from starva\ntion one of these children of sorrow.\nThe Near East Relief, comprising a\nband of the most prominent Christian\nmen and women of the nation and the\nstate of Wisconsin, beseeches the teach\ners and pupils of this great state to make\na small sacrifice of time and money in\norder to save their Christian brothers\nand sisters in the land of the Divine\nChild. Their hungry eyes are looking\nacross the sea at the well fed American\nboys and girls and their longing hands\nreadb out asking for bread.\nBy adopting one of these orphans, by\nj signing a pledge to furnish food, a pupil\nor group of pupils in every grade, in\nevery school of Wisconsin can bring a\n1 smile to each child of sorrow.\nWon\u2019t you do for one of these, of\nwhom the Master said, \"As ye do unto\nthe least of these, so do ye unto Me.\u201d\nSincerely.\nThe Wisconsin State Committee\nNear East Relief.\nSend all money collected for this\npurpose, to the county superintendent of\nschools.\nWhen Miss Bradley attended the coun\nty superintendents\u2019 convention at Madi\nson recently, the governor announced\nthat any superintendent who desired to\njdo so, could receive enough volumes of\nthe book, entitled, Wisconsin in the\nWorld War, to place in all the schools of\ntheir respective counties. These were to\ntie sent free, subject only to transporta\ntion. Miss Bradley has written to the\ngovernor, for forty volumes of this book,\nto place in all the schools in the county.\nThere is a bill brought up in the state\nI legislature, which is now in session, as\nto whether the teachers\u2019 retirement law,\nI should be reduced from twenty-live to\ntwenty years. Miss Bradley has written\nto our assemblyman, Mr. Mark, stating\nthat the committee of common schools,\npeople and herself approve of this\nmeasure.\nWe are to place in every rural school\nand state graded school in the county,\na printed list of all the names of the\ngraduates of that respective school dat\ning back for the last 15 years. This will\nserve as an incentive for the pupils in\nthe grades, to follow in the footsteps of\nthese graduates,\u2014to go onward in their\nwork until the goal is reached.\nThe following are the pupils who won\nthe prizes for the best essay on \"Tuber\nculosis, A Curable and Preventable\nI Disease.\u201d The winner will receive a $lO\nprize. The money received will go to\nthe school though rather than the pupil,\nj A gift in form of a picture would be an\nexcellent remembrance of this occasion.\nRuth Brown, $lO, Bth grade essay, Spring\nstead school. The prize for the best 6th\nand 7th grade essay went to the Curry\nand Gurney pupils. As we haven\u2019t re\ni ceived their names, as yet, the winners\u2019\nnames will be announced next week.\nThe Van Buskirk state graded school\nunder the direction of the instructor.\nMrs. Ed Anderson, has organized a gar\nment making club for the girls and a\nstock judging club for the boys.\nMrs. Marion Vonderheid of theSpring\nj stead school, Miss Ellen Olson of the\nCentral school and Miss Alice Jackson\n|of the Simon school have purchased a\nhot lunch equipment for their schools.\nHot lunches will be served daily to the\npupils.\nPlacements Of Labor.\nDuring 1929 the eleven free employ\nment offices conducted by the Indus\ntrial commission made P 1,570 place\nments as com jra red with 02,00 sin 1019.\nOf the persons placed76,ols were men\nand 15.5t\u2018<0 women. No person is coun\nted as placed, unless the employer to\nwhom he was referred reports that\nIn* has been hired. Approximately\nto percent of the total placements were\nin Milwaukee and i>o percent in the 10\noffices in the smaller cities.\nDuring December, 1920, the employ\nment offices placed a total of 4,367\npersons as compared with 5,555 in\nDecember, 1919, This falling off re j\ntlecis the change in industrial condi\ntions. Increases over a year ago oc- j\neurred in Ashland. Green Hay, Madi- j\nson. Oshkosh, and Rhinelander. The\nhulk of the persons placed were un\nskilled workmen, with a considerable\nfalling off in the number of the\nplacements in skilled and clerical\nhelp. There is marked increase, ou\nthe other hand, in the number of\nwomen domestics placed. iff tbe i\ntotal ot 1 497 placements of womenj\nduring this month no !tss than 1,20 s\nwere domestics.\nHeard in a Restaurant.\n\u201cHere,, waiter, nsk the wrehostra t\u00ab\nplay the Toreador song while 1 <*at thli\nsteak 1 like to f> e! tike a t.ul! tighter.'\nHOOVER RESTORED\nTO FULL STRENGTH\n\u201cTanlac Is Wonderfnl and I Have\nStarted My Wife Takiug If,\u201d\nHe Says.\n\u201cI'm glad to endorse Tanlac for all\nthey claim for it, since it has built me\nup and put me iu such line shape,\u201d\nsaid Philip Hoover, foreman for the\nHayward Linotype Go., living at 874\n44t li St., Milwaukee, Wis.\n\u201cA year ago last January I had a\nhad attack of the \u2019flu\u2019and my stom\nach got all out of order. Everything\n1 ate seemed to ferment aud 1 would\nbloat up \u00abs tight as a drum. Cramps\nin my stomach would almost double\nnte up, aud at times 1 became dizzy\nwhen I would bend over. My legs\nwould ache and pain me dreadfully\nand I was so nervous and restless\ncould scarcely sleep. 1 was weak aud\nworn out, couldn\u2019t eat enough to do\nany good and was very much worried\nover my miserable condition.\n\u201c1 saw. so much about the good\nTanlac was doing that l decided to try\njl myself, and since taking five bot\ntles my appetite is splendid and my\nstomach never bothers me, for I eat\nanything 1 want without its troubling\nme a bit. I\u2019m entirely free from\nbloating, cramps and dizziness, and\nmy nerves are in such good order that\nI sleep like a top every night. I\u2019m\nfull of energy till the time and am\nfeeling just Hue iu every way. Tau\nlae has restoied my health so com\npletely that I\u2019ve started my wife on\nit now and 1 simply think it\u2019s the\ngrandest medicine ever sold.\u201d\nTanlac is sold iu Hurley at Whit\nman\u2019s Pharmacy.\nEconomic System at Fault.\nThat the present stale of business\ndepression rests upon the fundament\nal unsoundness of our economic sys\ntem is the view of Director Nordman\nof the Market Division expressed in\na statement issued at Madison. \u201cThe\nremedy does not lie-in a change of\nfeeling.\u201d says Mr. Nordman, \u201cor in\nthe assumption ot an air of optimism\nas is advocated by some. The difficul\nties which the country is going\nthrough are not products of imagina\ntion not are they the result of the\nwar alone. The economic defects\nwhich produced them existed\u2019 long\nago. The war has only intcnsitiedthese\ndifficulties and no amount of optimis\ntic newspaper publicity, of soothing\nprophecies as to the future or of the\npatching tip and restoring confidence\nprocesses will ever eliminate them.\n\u201cConditions are not economically\nsound when the farmer cannot sell at\na fair and just price all he produces,\nand the consumer is not in a position\nto buy all he reasonably needs; they\nare not sound while many legalized\nprivileges exist in the country, as are\nshown to exist by tiie vast fortunes\nand stupendous incomes acquired. I\nam not speaking of fortunes earned;\nthe owners of tiiese have conferred\nbenefits upon society greater than\nthat which they acquired.\nThe farmer\u2019s full share of the\njuice of liis products is considerably\nreduced because of inflated land val\nues. a monopolistic control of the\nmarket in certain lines of trade, and\nthe waste and unnecessary expenses\ninherent in our system of distribu\ntion. Oifthe other hand, the consum\ner's share of his arnings is reduced\nby the legalized privileges which re\nsult in enormous incomes acquired\nby a privileged few. If a considerable\nminority has tlie* power to acquire\nmore than it is rightfully entitled\nto it logically follows that the ma\njority gets less than that to which\nit has a just claim. This majority will\nhave to deprive itself of much that\nit needs,thus making less demands on\nthe commodities which are produced.\nAnd here is the fundamental cause\nof poor markets, of more commodi\nties being produced than are sold,\nof had times, unemployment and all\nthe other conditions that everyone is\ncomplaining of.\u201d\nMr. Nordman believes it to be one\nof the duties imposed on his otliee to\ncall attention to what is deemed to\nlie the causes of the present business\ndepression. The remedies for these\ntroubles are discussed in the jiress\nletters which the Division of Markets\nis periodically issuing.\n\nConstipation.\nConstipation of the bowels is a stop\nj\u00bbage of the sewerage system that\nremoves waste matter from the body.\nIt is as necessary that your bowels\nmove regularly once each day. to\ncarry off this waste, as it is that the\nwaste pipes of your home be kept\nopen and carry off the waste from\nthe house. If you would enjoy good\nhealth, keep your bowels regular by\ntaking Chamberlain's Tablets when\nneeded.\n\nlllMatched Pair.\n\"A short temper and a long head\nrarely go together.\u201d\u2014Forbes Maga\nzine.\nChamberlain\u2019s Cough Remedy.\nThis is a pleasant, safe and reliable\nmedicine for coughs and colds. It\nhas been in use for many years and\nit- held in high esteem in those house\nholds where its good qualities are\nbest known. It is a favorite with\nmothers of young children, as it con\ntains no opium or other harmful\ndrug. Try it when you have need of\n\u25a0inch a remedy.\nGet your meals at\nThe Quick Case\nNow serving Fresh Oysters\non shell\nTry our Regular Dinners\n45c and 50c\nGertie Building;\nHurley\nr-\nTwin City Fuel Yards\nMenry Carter, Prop.\nDealer In all